In JavaScript, you can use the `localStorage` object to store data in the browser's storage. Here are examples of saving data to localStorage and reading it back:

**Saving Data to Local Storage:**
```javascript
// Save a string value to localStorage with key "username"
localStorage.setItem("username", "johndoe");

// Save an object to localStorage with key "userData"
var user = {
  name: "John Doe",
  age: 30,
  email: "john@example.com"
};
localStorage.setItem("userData", JSON.stringify(user));
```

**Reading Data from Local Storage:**
```javascript
// Read a string value from localStorage with key "username"
var username = localStorage.getItem("username");
console.log(username); // Outputs: johndoe

// Read an object from localStorage with key "userData"
var userDataJSON = localStorage.getItem("userData");
if (userDataJSON) {
  var userData = JSON.parse(userDataJSON);
  console.log(userData); // Outputs: {name: "John Doe", age: 30, email: "john@example.com"}
} else {
  console.log("No user data found in localStorage");
}
```

Note that the `localStorage` object can only store string values. If you want to save an object or other non-string value, you need to convert it to a JSON string using `JSON.stringify()` and then parse it back into an object when reading it from localStorage using `JSON.parse()`.
